ut 1340–":"circa 1340–Overleden","1341–Female":"1341–Overleden","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1340":"circa 1340","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Tybeste, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"en":{"about 1340–":"about 1340–Deceased","1341–Female":"1341–Deceased","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1340":"about 1340","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Tybeste, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thorley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire): habitational name, in most cases probably a variant of   Thornley  , although there are places called Thorley (in Hertfordshire and in Lincolnshire), which could have contributed to the surname; these are also named from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn bush’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’."],"variants":[{"name":"Thawley","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Derbyshire): variant of   Thorley  ."]},{"name":"Thornley","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from Thornley in Lancashire, and perhaps also from Thornyleigh near Heaton in Leek (Staffordshire) and Thornleigh in Huddersfield (Yorkshire). The Lancashire name derives from Old English <i>thornede</i> ‘thorny’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The other placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ or <i>thornig</i> ‘thorny’ + <i>lēah</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":115,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Thorley of Bybeste was born about 1340, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Dama En Blanco. He died in Suffolk, England."},"